1 TITL United States World War I Draft Registrations, 1917-1918
1 PUBL MyHeritage
1 TEXT When the United States declared war on the German Empire on April 6, 1917 its standing army was comprised of approximately 100,000 men with another 115,000 in National Guard units. President Wilson im
2 CONC mediately directed the Department of War to work to increase the army to a one million-man force. However, six weeks after war was declared only 73,000 new recruits had volunteered for military servic
2 CONC e.
2 CONC Military planners and political leaders had correctly anticipated the general apathy in the nation for the war effort at its onset and almost as soon as war was declared work began in the US Congress 
2 CONC to enact updated conscription legislation. Congress passed the Selective Service Act on May 18, 1917. This act authorized the federal government to raise a national army through compulsory enlistment.
2 CONC The initial Selective Service Act required all men aged 21 to 30 to register. In August 1918, at the request of the War Department, Congress amended the law to expand the age range to include all men 
2 CONC aged 18 to 45.
2 CONC Three specific registrations were conducted: 
2 CONC <ul><li>June 5, 1917. This first registration was for all men between the ages of 21 and 31.</li><li>June 5, 1918. The second registration was for those who had turned 21 after June 5, 1917 and a supp
2 CONC lemental registration included in the second registration was held on August 24, 1918, for those who turned 21 years old after June 5, 1918.</li><li>September 12, 1918. The third, and final registrati
2 CONC on was for all men aged 18 through 45 not previously enrolled.</li></ul>
2 CONC By the end of the First World War, some 2 million men had volunteered for military service and 2.8 million other men had been drafted. Accordingly, a draft registration does not imply that the individ
2 CONC ual ended up being drafted or that he didnãt volunteer separately. 
2 CONC The handwriting on the card is normally that of a registration board worker usually labeled the ãregistrarã. However, almost all cards contain the signature or ãmarkã in the handwriting of the
2 CONC  registrant himself.
1 _TYPE Collection
1 _MEDI 10513
0 @S500158@ SOUR
1 _UPD 24 APR 2023 00:55:28 GMT -0500 
1 TITL United States Passport Applications, 1795-1925
1 PUBL MyHeritage
1 TEXT <p>It is important for genealogists to note that prior to 1952 US passports were generally not required for international travel. There were only two time periods during the span of this collection wh
2 CONC en passports were required for traveling internationally: during the Civil War and World War I. Many individuals who traveled internationally will not appear on any passport index simply because passp
2 CONC orts were not required. However, passports were of particular benefit to naturalized US citizens traveling abroad as the passport reduced the likelihood that their birth country would try to detain th
2 CONC em or prevent their return to the United States.</p>
2 CONC <p>In addition to this passport collection, it may be beneficial to search passenger manifests. While an individual may not have needed a passport to travel internationally, they will be listed on a U
2 CONC S citizen manifest. However, the information found on US citizen manifests is sparse compared to the information found on later passport applications.</p>
2 CONC <p>It was also rare for a single passport to cover multiple trips abroad. Many wealthy US citizens appear multiple times within this collection because they applied for a new passport with every voyag
2 CONC e.</p>
1 _TYPE Collection
1 _MEDI 10720
0 @S500159@ SOUR
1 _UPD 24 APR 2023 00:56:12 GMT -0500 
1 TITL U.S. Social Security Applications and Claims, 1936-2007
1 PUBL MyHeritage
1 TEXT <p>Starting in 1936 the Social Security Administration started to maintain records of each individual who applied for a Social Security Number. The earliest form of these records were known as the ã
2 CONC Master Files of the Social Security (SSN) Holders and SSN Applicationsã. This was more commonly known simply as the ãEnumeration Systemã. In the 1970s legacy records from this system were migrat
2 CONC ed and new records were maintained electronically in the Numerical Identification System (NUMIDENT).</p>
2 CONC <p>This collection contains records of individuals with a verified death between 1936 and 2007 or who would have been over 110 years old by December 31, 2007. There are three types of entries in NUMID
2 CONC ENT: applications (SS-5), claims, and death entries. The records of applications and claims are presented here in this collection. The death entries are available on MyHeritage as the <a id="" href="h
2 CONC ttps://www.myheritage.com/research/collection-10002/" class="green">U.S. Social Security Death Index (SSDI).</a></p>
2 CONC <p>The application (SS-5) records contain information extracted from the SS-5 form ãApplication for a Social Security Cardã or ãApplication for Social Security Account Number.ã Information in 
2 CONC the NUMIDENT application entries include applicantãs full name, fatherãs name, motherãs maiden name, sex, race/ethnic description, place of birth, and other information about the application and
2 CONC  subsequent changes to the applicantãs record - such as name changes especially common (and even required) when women marry. For about 43 percent of social security numbers, there are multiple appli
2 CONC cation records.</p>
2 CONC <p>The application records preserved by the Social Security Administration do not include records of all social security applications between 1936 and 2007. Information of applications prior to 1973 m
2 CONC ay be incomplete. There may not be a record for an individual in both the application records and the death entries and there are nearly 6 million social security numbers in the application records th
2 CONC at do not appear in the death entries. And conversely, there are records in the death entries that have no corresponding extant record in the application entries.</p>
2 CONC <p>The claim records include information on the type of claim, the claimantãs full name, date of birth, gender, and for about half of the claim records the US state or country of birth. For a small 
2 CONC number of social security numbers there are multiple claim records.</p>
2 CONC <p>Records in this collection may have place names that were abbreviated or personal names that were truncated in the data supplied by the Social Security Administration. MyHeritage has corrected and 
2 CONC expanded many of these when possible but other values remain abbreviated or truncated.</p>
1 _TYPE Collection
1 _MEDI 10863
0 @S500160@ SOUR
1 _UPD 24 APR 2023 13:17:24 GMT -0500 
1 TITL 1940 United States Federal Census
1 PUBL MyHeritage
1 TEXT We undertook the arduous task of deciphering the handwritten pages of the 1940 Census to create a searchable index for the census. This was accomplished gradually, state by state, as we covered more a
2 CONC nd more of the census.
2 CONC As required by the US Constitution, the census is a federal mandate to count every resident of the United States of America every 10 years. Census data is released to the public 72 years after it was 
2 CONC taken.
2 CONC Federal census takers were asked to record information about every person who was in each household on the census day. A census taker might have visited a house on a later date, but the information he
2 CONC  collected was supposed to be about the people who were in the house on the census day. The basic census enumeration unit was the county. Each county was divided into enumeration districts, one for ea
2 CONC ch enumerator. The completed forms were sent to the Commerce Department's Census Office in Washington, D.C.
2 CONC Federal censuses are usually reliable, depending on the knowledge of the informant and the care of the census enumerator. Information may have been given to a census taker by any member of the family 
2 CONC or by a neighbor. Some information may have been incorrect or deliberately falsified.
1 _TYPE Collection
1 _MEDI 10053
0 @S500161@ SOUR
1 _UPD 24 APR 2023 13:22:07 GMT -0500 
1 TITL Connecticut, Marriages
1 PUBL MyHeritage
1 TEXT The index contains records from each of the eight counties of Connecticut. The counties with the highest number of records are Fairfield, New Haven, and Hartford, respectively. These three counties ma
2 CONC ke up over three quarters of the index. The records in this collection are from the Connecticut State Library website.
1 _TYPE Collection
1 _MEDI 11008
0 @S500162@ SOUR
1 _UPD 24 APR 2023 13:24:38 GMT -0500 
1 TITL U.S. City Directories
1 PUBL MyHeritage
1 TEXT <p>The consolidated records in this collection often tell a wider story about a person: They allow a researcher to learn when a person married or divorced, and in some cases deduce when the head of th
2 CONC e household or their spouse died. They also help track changes in workplace or occupation and reveal when a person moved from one location to another.</p>
2 CONC <p>City directories, like census records, contain information that helps genealogists establish residences, occupations, and relationships between individuals. The added benefit of city directories is
2 CONC  that they were published annually in many cities and towns throughout the United States.</p>
2 CONC <p>MyHeritage corrected errors in the original Optical Character Recognition (OCR) scans of the directory pages, and then employed several advanced technologies, including Record Extraction, Name Enti
2 CONC ty Recognition, and Conditional Random Fields to parse the data, and correct errors in the original OCR output of the directory pages. Training a machine learning model how to parse raw free-text reco
2 CONC rds into names, occupations, and addresses enabled the production of a structured, searchable index of valuable historical information. Optical Character Recognition may introduce mistakes in some rec
2 CONC ords, and the use of machine learning to parse these records may create mistakes as well. Therefore, as with any genealogical record, users are encouraged to consult the original images and fix any mi
2 CONC stakes they may find when extracting information into their family trees.</p>
2 CONC <p>The records in this collection date back to the 1800s and are an excellent resource for creating a more informed picture of family life during the intervening years between censuses. Of particular 
2 CONC note is the strength of city directories in filling in the genealogical gap caused by the destruction of almost all of the 1890 U.S. Federal Census schedules. The 20-year period between the 1880 Censu
2 CONC s and the 1900 Census has long been a challenge in family history research, and city directories on MyHeritage from this period serve as an important census substitute.</p>
2 CONC <p>City directories were first published in the U.S. in 1785, with directories from Philadelphia, New York City, Boston, and Baltimore being published before the end of the 18th century. The popularit
2 CONC y of these directories increased tremendously in the 19th century and reached their zenith during the latter part of the 20th century.</p>
2 CONC <p>Publishers of these directories employed local residents to canvas these cities and towns regularly to collect and update the data they included in their publications. The information collected var
2 CONC ies somewhat by year and publisher as practices evolved. For example, by the start of the 20th century, it was common to find the names of deceased spouses listed. Some publishers even collected and p
2 CONC ublished the names of recently deceased residents with their age at death and full death date. City directories were most commonly published under the name of a primary city but often contain the same
2 CONC  information for nearby smaller cities and towns.</p>
2 CONC <p>This collection will be updated soon to include pre-1860 directories as well as a large and unique set of directories published after 1960.</p>
1 _TYPE Collection
1 _MEDI 10705
0 @S500163@ SOUR
1 _UPD 24 APR 2023 13:32:47 GMT -0500 
